            <div type="note">
                <head type="title">Grace Allen (<!--Entry needed here.-->)</head>
                <p>Eldest daughter<!--Correction needed here.--> of <persName corresp="#GA">George Allen</persName>. In <date when="1901">1901</date>, along with her brothers <persName corresp="#ALLENH">Hugh Allen</persName>
                    and <persName corresp="#ALLENW">William Allen</persName>, she became a member of the board of the publishing business
                    now named <orgName corresp="#GEORGEALLEN">George Allen and Sons</orgName>. <persName corresp="#ALLENG">Grace</persName> had an important role in preparing many
                    of her <persName corresp="#GA">father</persName>&#x02BC;s late&#x2010;century publications of
                    <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s early works. <persName corresp="#WGC">W. G. Collingwood</persName> says in <title type="book" corresp="#JRPOEMS1891"><hi rend="italic"
                        >Poems</hi></title> ([<date when="1891">1891</date>], 1:268) that she transcribed poems for that edition from
                    her father&#x02BC;s copy of the scarce <title type="book" corresp="#JRPOEMS1850"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi>
                    (<date when="1850">1850</date>)</title>.</p>
                <p>See <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#DAWSONPEOPLESRUSKIN"><persName corresp="#PDAWSON">Dawson</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#DAWSONPEOPLESRUSKIN"><hi rend="italic">People&#x2019;s Ruskin</hi></title></ref>, 10.</p>
            </div>
